body:
I really like the idea of the change, but I believe it will break *a lot* of existing scripts.  Take this function for example.

```powershell
function Test-Function {
    [CmdletBinding()]
    param()
    begin {
        # Arbitrary intialization code
        if (-not (Get-Module ModuleThatMightChangeCodePath)) {
            Write-Warning 'Recommended module was not found'
        }
    }
    end {
        if ($false) {
            # Conditional error hit, caller can use `ErrorAction` to determine how this is handled.
            Write-Error 'Possible problem!'
        }

        # Do real work. This won't be hit if Get-Module writes a non-terminating error and
        # ErrorAction is stop
        return $true
    }
}

# Returns $true if condition is not hit.
Test-Function -ErrorAction Stop

function Get-Module {
    [CmdletBinding()]
    param([string] $Name)
    end {
        Write-Error 'Not found'
    }
} 

# Always fails during initialization
Test-Function -ErrorAction Stop
```

This is something I do pretty frequently.  Use a command like `Get-Module` while doing some validation and then continue on with the rest of the command.  Now since the error `Get-Module` would throw is non terminating, alone it doesn't really affect anything.  But if I use this function in a script, and I expect to be able to force that *expected* error to be terminating, that function breaks unexpectedly.

I suspect this is a pretty common pattern, and the discussed change would significantly hurt script portability if it was made across the board.
